  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Silk, Feathering, and Those Ears" imageAlt="Cavalier King Charles Spaniel puppy having its silky ears brushed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Cavalier coat is genuinely low-effort for how good it looks: brush 2 to 3 times a week, paying attention to the feathering behind the ears and legs where tangles start, an occasional bath, and no clipping required, though many Singapore owners keep the feathering trimmed for the humidity. Expect moderate year-round shedding.</p>
      <p>The real weekly appointment is the ears. Long, heavy drop ears trap warmth and moisture, our climate's speciality, and unchecked they brew infections. Once a week: lift, look, sniff, and wipe with the cleanser from your starter kit. Yeasty smell or head shaking means a vet visit, early, when it's cheap and simple.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Cavalier Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Cavalier King Charles Spaniel puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Cavalier goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. And then there is the conversation every honest Cavalier page must have: mitral valve disease. This heart condition affects Cavaliers at far higher rates than almost any breed, typically emerging in middle age, and it is the main reason the breed's lifespan is quoted as 10 to 14 rather than 14 to 16. It is not a reason to avoid the breed; it is a reason to own one knowingly: annual vet checks that include listening to the heart, from around age five, catch it early, and modern management gives affected dogs good years.</p>
      <p>The rest of the list is manageable: weekly ear care as above, eye checks for this large-eyed breed, and weight discipline, because a plump Cavalier's heart works harder. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Cavalier's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Cavalier puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Cavalier explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. This breed settles through proximity: the playpen where it can see people, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment, and Cavaliers settle fastest of all when they can hear you.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and the shadow behaviour begins; enjoy it. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week, and start practising short, boring departures now, five minutes at a time, so alone-time skills grow before they're needed. See what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

